'''HMS ''Erin's Isle''''' was a United Kingdom passenger [[paddle steamer]] built by [[A. & J. Inglis|A&J Inglis]] for the [[Belfast and County Down Railway]] (B&CDR). She was launched in [[Glasgow]] in 1912 as '''PS ''Erin's Isle''''', and sailed regular services on [[Belfast Lough]] until 1915.

She was then was requisitioned for the [[Royal Navy]] and became the [[Minesweeper (ship)|minesweeper]] HMS ''Erin's Isle''. On 7 February 1919 she was sunk by a [[Sea mine|mine]] off [[Nore]].<ref>[http://www.naval-history.net/WW1NavyBritishAdmiraltyEstimates1919.htm Admiralty Estimates for 1919] accessed 25 October 2016</ref>{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}} with the loss of 23 lives.{{sfn|Hanlan|1919}}

==With the B&CDR==
The B&CDR had owned and run steamships since 1893, mainly between [[Belfast]] and [[Bangor, County Down|Bangor]] but also to other destinations in [[County Down]] and [[County Antrim]].

At the end of the 1911 summer season the railway planned to sell {{PS|Slieve Bearnagh}}, which dated from 1894,{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=13}} and replace her with a new, larger and more modern ship. The company ordered ''Erin's Isle'' from A&J Inglis of Pointhouse, Glasgow, who launched her on 12 June 1912{{sfn|McCutcheon|1980|p=149}} and fitted her out in less than a month.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}} The B&CDR named her after "[[Erin]]", the [[Hiberno-English]] version of the [[Irish language|Irish]] ''Éirinn'', meaning Ireland.

''Erin's Isle'' entered B&CDR service on 12 July 1912.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}} She worked seasonally from mid-May to the end of September each year, making regular scheduled runs between Belfast and Bangor and between Bangor and [[Larne]], plus excursions from Bangor to other destinations.{{sfn|McCutcheon|1980|p=149}} She ended her fourth summer season on 29 September 1915.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}}

==With the Royal Navy==
{{location map|England south of the Humber and east of the Isle of Wight|width=200
|lat= 51.55
|long= 1.32
|caption=The wreck of ''Erin's Isle'' lies in North Edinburgh Channel, north of [[Thanet]].
}}
The [[Admiralty]] inspected ''Erin's Isle'' on 8 October 1915, and then requisitioned her on 20 November for £400 per month.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}} Six days later she sailed from Belfast to become the [[Royal Navy]] auxiliary [[Minesweeper (ship)|minesweeper]] HMS ''Erin's Isle''.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}}

''Erin's Isle'' remained in Royal Navy service after the [[Armistice with Germany]]. On 6 February 1919 she sailed from [[Sheerness]] on the [[Isle of Sheppey]] and anchored for the night in the North Edinburgh Channel off the [[Thames Estuary]],{{sfn|Hanlan|1919}} not far from the [[Nore]] sandbank.<ref name=Clyde/> At 0600 hrs on 7 November she was still at anchor and her crew were called to rise.{{sfn|Hanlan|1919}} About five minutes later a drifting [[Sea mine|mine]] struck the forward part of her [[starboard]] side beneath the seamen's quarters, blowing her practically in two.{{sfn|Hanlan|1919}} She sank in about two minutes with the loss of 23 lives.{{sfn|Hanlan|1919}} 28 survivors were rescued,<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Mine-sweeper sunk by mine |day_of_week=Saturday |date=8 February 1919 |page_number=5 |issue=42019 |column=C }}</ref> of whom only about three were seamen from the quarters where the mine had struck.{{sfn|Hanlan|1919}}

The Admiralty paid £53,676 compensation to the B&CDR for the loss of the ship but the railway found that a new ship would cost £64,000.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}} Given the changed economic circumstances after the First World War the company decided not to replace her.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}}

==Wreck and war grave==
The wreck of ''Erin's Isle'' lies in the North Edinburgh Channel off the [[Thames Estuary]].{{sfn|Wessex Archaeology|2004|p=18}} In 2001 the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] (MoD) began a rolling programme of assessment of wrecks for possible protection as [[war grave]]s under the [[Protection of Military Remains Act 1986]]. In August 2004 the [[Port of London Authority]] was advised that the MoD had not designated wreck as a [[Protection of Military Remains Act 1986#Criteria for designation of wrecks|protected place]] under the Act, but could decide to do so in future.{{sfn|Wessex Archaeology|2004|p=18}}

